SPECIES COMMENTS: Clark's nutcrackers flying in groups 2-4 continously from locked gate to plateau ridge. Peter R. walked to the North end of the ridge and discovered a narrow gap in the valley that the birds were "funneling" through. A count was initiated from 1130 to 1610 hrs and over 500 birds were counted. (502 to be exact). The birds seemed to be flying along a narrow corridor and all pretty much followed the exact same path. Prior to the "official" count likely in range of 50 birds would have been sighted and are in addition to the 500 count posted. Birds were still coming through after the "official" count period, but we needed to return to avoid too much driving in the darkness.
Saw 63 nutcrackers from approx 0900 to 1300 - some possible double counts and a further 19 nutcrackers from approx 1300 to 1400 hrs generally heading in a Southerly direction

TRIP COMMENTS: Incidental birding on a day of hiking and scrambling

Hiking and birding with Sharon and Robyn Reeve. We walked to the end of the Parker Ridge Trail, enjoying the great views of the Saskatchewan Glacier and the headwaters of the Saskatchewan River, not to mention a pair of Prairie Falcons that flew by multiple times and chased each other repeatedly in front of and over the cliffs where they likely nested, or are currently nesting. I was very surprised to hear what I was sure was a Canyon Wren singing from a steep scree slope near the top of Parker Ridge. The location was on the west side of the ridge, about half way from where the trail reaches the ridge top and the end of the ridge trail to the south. It called multiple times its loud, clear, descending teer-teer-teer-teer-teer-too, each note clear, downslurred and lower than the previous, with the "too" note rough and somewhat buzzy. I was below the trail when I heard it call multiple times, so I climbed back up to where Sherrie and Robyn were, drawing their attention to the call. Sherrie agreed that it was a Canyon Wren, a song we are both very familiar with, but we were unable to see it or photograph it. Due to the location and distance from its normal range, I regret that I was unable to document this occurrence with more than just my hearing a familiar call. Weather: cloudless skies but hazy due to smoke from distant fires, warm 60 to 75 degrees F, calm at the trailhead but winds building to 25 mph on Parker Ridge by mid day.

TRIP COMMENTS: This is a typical montane Rocky Mountain foothills ridge in SW Alberta.  Primarily grass and low forbes on the SW facing slopes, a rocky spine and mixed Douglas Fir, spruce, pine interspersed with grassland, aspen and larger understory shrubs (with berries) on the NE facing side.  During fall migration the rocky ridge and NE facing areas load up with groups of passerines and that was the case today.
